{{Infobox supercluster | name = Horologium [[Supercluster]] | image = Hor.gif | image_size = 400px | caption = A map of the Horologium Supercluster | credit = | epoch = | constellation = [[Horologium (constellation)|Horologium]] and [[Eridanus (constellation)|Eridanus]] | ra = {{RA|03|19}} | dec = {{DEC|-50|02}} | brightest_member = | member_no = | major_axis_mpc = {{convert|169|Mpc|Mly|0|abbr=on|lk=on}} | minor_axis_mpc = <!-- {{convert|000|Mpc|Mly|0|abbr=on|lk=on}} {{hub|0.00}} --> | redshift = | distance = {{convert|291.4|Mpc|Mly|0|abbr=on|lk=on}} | mass = ~10<sup>17</sup> | luminosity = | flux = | other_names = Horologium-Reticulum Supercluster }} The '''Horologium Supercluster''', also known as the '''Horologium-Reticulum Supercluster''', is a massive [[supercluster]] spanning around 550 million light-years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasoftheuniverse.com/superc/hor.html|title=The Horologium Supercluster|website=www.atlasoftheuniverse.com|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref> It has a mass of around 10<sup>17</sup> [[sun|solar masses]], similar to that of the [[Laniakea Supercluster]], which houses the [[Milky Way]]. It is centered on coordinates [[right ascension]] {{RA|03|19}} and [[declination]] {{DEC|&minus;50|02}}, and spans an angular area of 12° × 12°.<ref name=apj130_3/>
The nearest part of the supercluster is 700 million [[light-year]]s away from Earth, while the far end of it is 1.2 billion light-years. It is visible in the [[constellation]]s [[Horologium (constellation)|Horologium]] and [[Eridanus (constellation)|Eridanus]]. The Horologium Supercluster has about 5,000 [[galaxy group]]s (30,000 giant galaxies and 300,000 [[dwarf galaxies]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasoftheuniverse.com/superc/hor.html|title=The Horologium Supercluster|website=www.atlasoftheuniverse.com|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref> It includes the galaxy cluster [[Abell 3266]].
